    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-07-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-07-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="646"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d646">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.6131/644</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Chief of the Division of Commercial Policy
                        and Agreements</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Hawkins</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-07-30">July 30,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">For the Information of the Secretary of State:</hi>
                </p>
                <p>The exchange of notes continuing in force the Commercial Agreement of 1937, for
                    which an appointment has been made for you and the Russian Ambassador at 10 a.m.
                    July 31, provides that the agreement shall remain in force until August 6, 1943
                    and thereafter, unless superseded by a more comprehensive commercial agreement,
                    subject to termination on six months’ notice by either Government.</p>
                <p>At that time you will hand the Ambassador an <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>,
                    similar to the one given him last year with respect to coal.<note n="94"
                        xml:id="d646fn94">The text of the <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> of
                        July 31, 1942, regarding imports of coal from the Soviet Union, is identical
                        with the <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> of August 2, 1941, <ref
                            target="frus1941v01#pg_924">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 924</ref>.</note> This <hi rend="italic"
                        >aide-mémoire</hi>
                    <pb facs="0769" n="763" xml:id="pg_763"/> states that if at any time during the
                    life of the agreement it should appear that imports of Soviet coal into the
                    United States would exceed in any calendar year the figure of 400,000 tons
                    mentioned in the Soviet note of August 6, 1940 limiting exports of coal to the
                    United States, the Government of the United States would feel free to consult
                    with the Soviet Government with a view to arriving at a satisfactory adjustment
                    of the matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harry C. Hawkins</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
